Smart Campus Distributed Load Balancing System
Overview

This project implements a distributed edge–fog computing simulation designed to demonstrate how smart buildings can dynamically manage computational workloads using environmental sensor data.

The system models a smart campus environment where multiple buildings act as edge computing nodes, while a centralized fog node provides additional processing capacity when needed.

The objective of the system is to maintain balanced workloads across nodes while preventing overload conditions.

The system reacts dynamically to environmental and activity-based sensor inputs such as:

Temperature

Humidity

CO₂ (Air Quality)

Motion

Power Consumption

Occupancy (People)

Instead of waiting for overload, the system redistributes processing tasks when nodes begin to experience higher demand.

System Architecture

The system consists of five distributed nodes, each running inside Docker containers.

Node	Role	Location
node1	Edge Node	Library
node2	Edge Node	Lecturer Office
node3	Edge Node	Laboratory
node4	Edge Node	Classroom
fog1	Fog Node	Campus Fog Server
Edge Nodes

Edge nodes represent smart campus buildings.
Each node simulates environmental sensors and generates processing workloads based on sensor readings.

Fog Node

The fog node acts as a central processing fallback server.
If edge nodes cannot absorb additional workload, tasks are redirected to the fog node.

System Behaviour

The system continuously monitors the state of all nodes.

When a node begins to experience high demand, the monitoring service redistributes workload to other nodes with lower load.

This allows the distributed system to maintain balanced performance and avoid bottlenecks.

Sensor Model

Each building node simulates the following sensors:

Sensor	Description
People	Number of occupants in the building
Temperature	Indoor temperature conditions
Humidity	Air moisture level
CO₂	Air quality level
Motion	Activity detection level
Power	Energy consumption of devices

The sensors are dynamically related.

For example:

Increasing people raises temperature, humidity, and CO₂ levels

Higher motion increases power usage

Increased power usage may increase temperature

These relationships create a realistic simulation of building activity.

Maximum Threshold Detection

Each sensor has a defined maximum value.

If any sensor reaches its maximum threshold, the node status becomes:

MAX-REACHED

This indicates that the node has reached a critical operating condition.

The system then redistributes workload to other nodes to maintain stability.

Node Status Types

Nodes may display several operational states:

Status	Meaning
ACTIVE	Normal operation
MAX-REACHED	A sensor has reached its maximum threshold
BALANCING-SEND	Node transferring workload to another node
RECEIVING	Node receiving workload from another node
FOG-RECEIVING	Fog server receiving excess workload
Load Balancing Strategy

The monitoring service continuously checks node metrics such as:

CPU usage

Memory usage

Processing queue

Sensor-driven workload

When imbalance is detected:

The node with the highest processing demand becomes the sender.

Nodes with lower demand become receivers.

Excess processing tasks are transferred to receiver nodes.

If all edge nodes are heavily loaded, the fog node receives the excess workload.

Technologies Used

The system was implemented using the following technologies:

Python

Flask

Docker

Docker Compose

HTML / JavaScript Dashboard

Running the System
1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/smart-campus-distributed-system.git
cd smart-campus-distributed-system
2. Start the containers
docker-compose up --build

This will start all distributed nodes and the monitoring service.

3. Open the dashboard

Open a browser and go to:

http://localhost:5001

The dashboard allows you to:

Adjust sensor sliders

Simulate building activity

Monitor node metrics

Observe load balancing events

Example Demonstration Scenario

Increase CO₂ or temperature in the Library node.

The node reaches its maximum sensor threshold.

The node status becomes MAX-REACHED.

The monitoring service redistributes workload to another node.

The receiving node shows RECEIVING status.

The system load becomes balanced again.

Educational Purpose

This project demonstrates several important distributed systems concepts, including:

Edge Computing

Fog Computing

Distributed Monitoring

Dynamic Load Balancing

Sensor-Driven Processing

Performance Transparency

Fault-Tolerant Architecture

The system provides a simulation environment for studying distributed resource management and adaptive workload distribution.

